variables.value: Huh? After some <FUL:UMIBOZUMAN>burgers?\nI went overboard and can't finish 'em all—take a few of mine!
Top cram school in town?!\nThis is your chance to enroll?!
Sure you don't want in?\nWe'll be here!
Hmm, nobody's signing up yet...\nIf a push won't work, then I'll just pull them in!
Our goal is to\nensure repeat business.
Volume and portion\nsize will be key.
Looks like we're going\nto ramp up production.
Recently, castella parfaits at the café on <MNT:NAGUMO> Street\nhave gained notable popularity. We must diversify our sweets\nbeyond castella to stay competitive.
I want to offer castella in a simpler form, easier to eat on the go.\nSomething like crepes sold street-side could work.
Naturally, students are quite hungry after school.\nOur castella must offer both generous portions and good value.
The edges trimmed from freshly baked castella are called offcuts.\nThough technically scraps, they're delicious and well-liked.
You're from the <MNT:NAGUMOHARA> Junior High football team, correct?\nCongrats on reaching the nationals! The community is abuzz—\nand we're proud to support you.
In honor of the <MNT:NAGUMOHARA> team's top-four placement,\nwe're offering discounts on our four most popular castellas.
I've authorized shipping of commemorative castellas\nfor the football club's win. That's how confident I am.
Word of mouth is even more important in the age of social media.\nHeritage Breadworks must follow the trend\nby modernizing our promotional strategies.
Castella retains the image of a luxury home dessert.\nWe must devise novel marketing methods.
With summer coming, we're considering products\ntailored for active students. The station's heavy foot traffic\noffers plenty of opportunity.
Heritage Castella offcuts are sold only at the factory.\nOffering them as a limited item could attract younger customers.
We plan to donate part of our sales proceeds to the\n<MNT:NAGUMOHARA> football club during this period.\nAllow us to support you however possible.
Heritage Breadwork's best seller is our deluxe castella,\nwhich is popular as a gift and often outsells the standard version.
The manager and I have reviewed your recent game.\nThere's no question you can defeat the invincible Raimon!
<FLC:KAMEO> downs a massive lunch and grabs pizza after school...\nand he's still that quick on the pitch? It's such a weird combo!
I used to steer clear of the Old Shipyard,\nwhat with the sketchy people always around. But lately?\nHaven't seen a single one. Kinda weird, huh?
Some Northbright kids asked me to recommend cool after-school hangouts,\nbut like... isn't stumbling upon those spots your own part of the fun?
They'll at least make\nthe finals, I bet.
Must be a big pizza fan.
I saw my first match\nthe other day.
Omg omg! There's this long-haired hottie at <MNT:NAGUMOHARA>, right?!\nHe walked past me all serious and intense\nand I swear my heart actually skipped a beat!
He's like...\nglam in the best way!
That redhead in the <MNT:NAGUMOHARA> surf club? Total heartthrob.\nLike, the way he holds his board?? I almost fainted, I swear!
His voice is to die for...
You know <FLA:TABE>, the Football Frontier commentator?\nI'd only heard his voice before but then I saw him and—bam!\nInstant crush!
He's got that total bad\nboy vibe...
But he's sooo intense on\nthe pitch!!
Everyone says <FLC:SAKURAZAKI>'s all fights and fury,\nbut the way he chases that ball like it's life or death?!\nI literally melted. Right there on the spot!
So they're running a ship between Nagasaki and Tokyo now?\nFaster by plane, sure. But for a leisurely trip, a cruise sounds just right.
I booked a ticket on the cruise myself.\nWhile it cost me a pretty penny,\nI might just run into a celebrity or two.
They say those passengers were junior high students.\nA cruise from Tokyo to Nagasaki... quite the elegant way to travel.
Nagasaki's always had foreign influences sprinkled around town.\nMaybe that's why Eastwind feels so familiar.
Say, you look familiar...\nHave you perhaps taken the Tristar cruise lately?
I got all excited, thought they'd be sailing to Tokyo for the\nfinals... but of course, they're flying instead.
Maybe it's time I\npitched in too...
They say <MNT:NAGUMOHARA> has quite the football team.\nIf they make it to the finals, maybe I'll treat them to a cruise.\nAnywhere they want!
Suppose it was only a matter of time.
I'm always at the station, so the local reporters like to chat me up.\nLately, all they ask about is the <MNT:NAGUMOHARA> football team.
Can't trust a fish\nwith a mustache!
Always in tight schools.\nReal social swimmers.
Unlike flounders. Those\nguys just lie there.
Yeah, they just keep\ngoing round and round.
Like koi in a pond,\nalways making waves.
Sashimi's probably the way to go for perch.\nI don't quite trust myself to prep it, though.\nBest leave it to the fishmonger.
I always stop by this shop for fish as the manager's wonderful.\nHe'll teach you anything you want to know.
The manager slices it into sashimi for me.\nIt's perfect when I just need one more dish for dinner.
I do love a\ngood fried mackerel.
Fresh mackerel sashimi is always a treat,\nbut I must admit, I prefer my mackerel fried and crispy.
My little brother's at <MNT:NAGUMOHARA> and\nobsessed with the student council prez.\nHe's hunting down a "rare photo" from the entrance ceremony.
That whole baseball vs. football feud at <MNT:NAGUMOHARA>\ndragged on forever... Glad it's finally over.
I really hope he's\nready for that.
My brother's looking into Eastwind for study abroad.\nTrouble is, his English grades are hopeless.
I saw a video of the Odaiba Football Gardens, and it's huge.\nI just hope he doesn't get lost.
He really needs\nto limit his usage.
Lately he's been glued to social media, tracking the prez nonstop.\nI'm honestly scared he's turning into a stalker...
He's going to the finals to cheer on the football club, or so he says.\nReally, he's just excited to wave a banner for the prez.
I'm stuck on\nwhat gift to bring...
We've got someone new\non the team...
I've got a bit of a\ndilemma...
Got it! I'll do my best!
I've got a meeting with <LST:SAKURAZAKI> Inc...\nI can't afford to mess this up, but I still haven't picked a gift.
I've got dinner with that client soon and I'm a wreck...\nI heard they're into youth football, so I'd better study up fast.
Most schools are struggling with low birth rates\nthese days, but <MNT:NAGUMOHARA> is thriving.\nI'd love to hear how their chair runs things.
We got a new mid-career hire and they're amazing...\nI'm just worried I'll get pushed out as the rookie.
I had dinner with that client the other day. We started talking\nabout the Football Frontier, and it totally broke the ice!
My client's a diehard Royal Academy fan. I'd hate to lose to Royal,\nbut at the same time, if <MNT:NAGUMOHARA> wins...
Got a Tokyo trip lined up on finals day!\nShould finish work just in time to catch the game in person!
First time, and a big name like that. No wonder anyone'd be nervous.\nI've heard the exec has a sweet tooth, so maybe castella's the move?
In networking, what matters most is showing interest\nin the other person. Even if your hobbies don't match,\nit still makes a great impression.
Schools and businesses aren't the same,\nbut there's plenty to learn from both.\nStill, I can't find a thing about <MNT:NAGUMOHARA>'s chair...
Thinking you're not needed just because someone's good.\nThat's not how teams work, you know. It's the mix that makes it.
<MNT:NAGUMOHARA> is all about football now thanks to you guys.\nIf they've seen a match, I've got a conversation starter.
Sports fans live and die by the score. But at the end of the day,\nbusiness is business. They'll get it.
Shifted my schedule so I could see the finals.\nWork first, but I'm definitely making the most of it.
He's got one less\nmatch to cover.
The commentators don't\nhave it easy either.
He'll be more\nfired up than usual.
The food at C'est Bon Burger is filling, but it's a tad expensive.\nI'd go broke if I had it every day...
The owner's French. He said he was really inspired\nafter trying a handmade burger here in Nagasaki.
Watching the Football Frontier sure works up an appetite.\nI blame it on the C'est Bon ads that keep popping up...
Ever since I tried their fully loaded burger,\nno other place has been able to satisfy me.
C'est Bon Burger has stores even in Tokyo.\nIf you ask me though, nothing beats the original!
Wait, there's no C'est Bon at the Odaiba Football Gardens?\nIt's prime spectator cuisine!
C'est Bon Burger makes a point of only using locally sourced produce.\nFarm-fresh veggies take the taste to a whole new level.
Says the guy who\njumped on first.
<FUL:MIYABI> wields considerable influence in this town.\nI read that while his methods can be heavy-handed,\nhe's also sharp and dependable.
I'll have to read it\ncover to cover...
Are you the type to pore over instruction manuals and the like?\nI find it helps prevent getting blindsided by obscure rules.
I did wonder if Northbright's players could still compete...\nBut school mergers are common now, so the rules allow it.
The Kyushu tournament's almost here.\nNorthbright must still be stinging from the Spring Cup...\nI'll be cheering them on.
The Football Frontier regional qualifiers are here.\nNorthbright's going to blow right through the prelims, no sweat!
I'm glad we still get to see the old Northbright players in action...\nbut a loss is a loss. Guess I've got mixed feelings.
Gotta settle the score with Raimon after that Spring Cup.\nDon't you lose before you get the chance!
Ever since the merger with <MNT:NAGUMOHARA>, <FLC:SORAMIYA>'s\nbeen sharper than ever. Wonder what lit that fire in him?
It's finally time to face Raimon. As a Northbright fan—no,\na <MNT:NAGUMOHARA> fan—I'll be rooting for you with everything I've got!
